<section id="fs-idm142872640" class="free-response">
<title>Free Response</title>
<exercise id="fs-idm157830256">
<problem id="fs-idp1495776">
<para id="fs-idp14010448">Describe the pathway of electron transfer from photosystem II to photosystem I in light-dependent reactions.</para></problem>
<solution id="fs-idm158342224">
<label/>
<para id="fs-idm183692320">A photon of light hits an antenna molecule in photosystem II, and the energy released by it travels through other antenna molecules to the reaction center. The energy causes an electron to leave a molecule of chlorophyll <emphasis effect="italics">a</emphasis> to a primary electron acceptor protein. The electron travels through the electron transport chain and is accepted by a pigment molecule in photosystem I.</para>
</solution>
</exercise>
<exercise id="fs-idm88164432">
<problem id="fs-idm132276912">
<para id="fs-idp68485216">What are the roles of ATP and NADPH in photosynthesis?</para>
</problem>
<solution id="fs-idm123143120">
<label/>
<para id="fs-idm146644368">Both of these molecules carry energy; in the case of NADPH, it has reducing power that is used to fuel the process of making carbohydrate molecules in light-independent reactions.</para>
</solution>
</exercise>
